play, and their interaction with history. Taken together, this collection suggests that the history of empire needs to be, in part at least, a history of display and of reception.This book will be essential reading for scholars and students interested in British history, the history of empire, art history and the history of museums and collecting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBritain's colonies.  aBritish Empire.  aBritish elite.  aCaptain Cook.  aCrystal Palace.  aFrench Revolutionary.  aNapoleonic Wars.  achurches.  acountry houses.  acultural products.  aimperial superpower.  amissionary societies.  apublic consciousness.  asatirical peace print.1 aAuerbach, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarczewski, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFordham, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhuman, Nalini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Ashley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLongair, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacKenzie, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacKenzie, John M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcAleer, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcAleer, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSèbe, Berny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester U